Exploratory Data Analysis of Air quality data in Indian cities¶

Group :008¶

Section:003¶

Dataset Information¶

  • Source : Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/neomatrix369/air-quality-data-in-india-extended

  • Description :This file is available on "Kaggle" and the name of the dataset is "Air Quality Data in India Extended". In a search report on air pollution in India which is published by the Health Effects Institute in 2018,it is concluded that air pollution was associated for 1.1 million deaths in India in 2015. [4]

  • Future use : This dataset can be useful to prevent Air Pollution, which helps to higher authories to mitigate this problem.

yes , dataset contains null , incomplete records. Below mentioned are the number of null values for each column and it is clear that dataset has a lot of missing values because a certain number of rows have small records and many missing or Nan values.

-What are the inclusion criteria for your data?¶

The following variables are the inclusion criteria for this dataset: AQI, AQI Bucket and many gases like NO,CO, NO2, NOx, O3,which are harmful for humans and environment as well.

-Is the data segmented in groups?¶

yes, the data segmented into the groups for example, Regions are divided into cityand states.

- Is the data imbalanced (large number of the records represent a majority class and very few records represent the minority class)?¶

There are few records in the dataset which are imbalanced, as the observations in each entity are either having incomplete or blank values. Furthermore, numerous columns, such as city and state with division in a maximum number of records represent a majority class, while a small number of records represent a minority class.For instance, in the below horizontal bar graph AQI level has different values in the each state of India.

In [381]:
f, ax_ = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize = (20,10))
sns.barplot(data=station_day_transformed, x='AQI', y='State')
plt.title("AQI(Air quality) in diferent state")

Does the data has any outliers¶

From the below mentioned horizontal graph,it can be clearly seen that air quality changes due to different season and the points that are far away from the continuous points and lies between 1750 and 2000 AQI are outliers.

Analysis Questions¶

  1. Which year the percentage of air pollution is high?
  2. In which season the proportion of air pollution is less?
  3. Grouping the CO by city and calculating the average CO per city?
  4. In which city the average of NO gas is higher or lesser?
  5. In which city the average of NO2 gas is higher or lesser?
  6. In which State the average of NO gas is higher?
  7. How various gases affect various regions?
  8. The average of different gases in each city?
  9. Air quality per year

1. In Which year the percentage of air pollution is high?¶

In [414]:
city_day_date.groupby('year').size().plot(kind='pie', figsize=(6, 6), autopct='%1.2f%%')
plt.ylabel("")
plt.title("Percentage of Air pollution from the year 2015 to 2020")
## Reference[3]
Out[414]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Percentage of Air pollution from the year 2015 to 2020')

In this pie chart, 2019 at peak point in the proportion of air pollution, which was 30.50% and represents by purple colour. The rate of air pollution was quite less in 2015 and 2016,that was 5.04%-6.70%. Ratio of air pollution was mostly equal in the years of 2018 and 2020, it was approximately nearby a quarter whereas in 2017, this percentage was only 11.34%.

2. In which season the proportion of air pollution is less?¶

In [415]:

plt.ylabel("")
plt.title("The percentage of air pollution according to season")
## Reference[3]

It is noticed that, in winter, air pollution is very less in comparison to other seasons, that is only 17.4% while the ratio of air pollution in monsoon at highest point, this is about 15% more than winter. Moreover, post-monsoon and summer seasons are both approximately lies in 23.1%-27.4% in the percentage of air pollution.

The graph depicts the average CO per city, with Delhi coming in first with a value of around 2.25 and a dark blue colour. Furthermore, CO levels in Patna are less than 1.25, whereas CO levels in Gurugram and Amritsar are only 0.75, and CO levels in Visakhapatnam are slightly higher than in both cities
